The format specifier for strings is `%s`, so just use this instead:

    printf(&quot;enter the first sequence: &quot;);
    scanf(&quot;\n%s&quot;, str1);

    printf(&quot;enter the second sequence: &quot;);
    scanf(&quot;\n%s&quot;, str2);

As @AjayBrahmakshatriya commented: `\n` matches any number of `\n` characters.

The problem with `%c` when reading char with scanf is that it treats the newline as input, as I explained in this [example][1].

---

However, if I were you, I&#39;d just use [`fgets()`][2], like this:

    fgets(str1, sizeof(str1), stdin);
    fgets(str2, sizeof(str2), stdin);

If you go with this approach, you will then probably be interested in https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2693776/removing-trailing-newline-character-from-fgets-input?


  [1]: https://gsamaras.wordpress.com/code/caution-when-reading-char-with-scanf-c/
